metadata.name: Acequia #49
metadata.description:
Acequia (‚Äúah-seh-kee-uh‚Äù) - a Spanish adaptation of the Arabic word as-sƒÅqiya, meaning ‚Äúwater carrier‚Äù. 

In our second collaboration, Rich and Rick are back with our blend of generative code, intricate design, attention to detail, and a splash of charm. 

‚Ä®Acequias are traditional irrigation canals used to distribute rainwater and snowmelt along a complex network of narrow channels. They are found in Spain, the American Southwest, and northern Mexico, where they are essential for sustaining fields, orchards, and gardens in semi-arid regions. ‚Ä®‚Ä®
Our aim in this series is to capture the essence of these waterways in bold geometric designs. Each piece is inspired by a mountain village or town in Andalusia (southern Spain). 

The location determines the cube designs and construction rules that are used to build the final output. These are combined with striking day/night palettes, outline styles, scales, climates, and a few surprises of course!


Controls (in live view): 

- Press [p] to pause water animation 
- Press [e] to complete water animation 
- Press [r] to reset water animation 
- Press [s] to save the current image 
- Press [h] for a high-res output suitable for printing 
- Press [b] to toggle the border

metadata.name: Rangxel #456
Algoscapes | Rock-face #159
metadata.description:
Algoscapes | Rock-face is part of the live outdoor art installation - 'Computational Convergence' at India Art Fair, held from 9-12 February 2023 in New Delhi.

Algoscapes is an ongoing study in fostering an aesthetic of abstraction in landscapes through geometry and code. This piece builds on past work on generating abstract landscapes algorithmically. It is an attempt to capture the essence of naturally occurring rock-faces, to capture the diverse vocabularies ranging from the jagged edges of a mountain's summit to the flowing lines of a canyon wall. The result is a constantly evolving display of color and form, abstract yet reminiscent of the intricacies of the natural world.

'S' key to Save image. '1' and '2' keys for higher resolution images.

Karthik Dondeti (Twitter : @d0ndeti, Instagram : @karthik.dondeti)
Built with p5js.
Feb 2023

metadata.name: flow | meditations #464
metadata.description:
"flow | meditations" is part of the live outdoor art installation - 'Computational Convergence' at India Art Fair, held from 9-12 February 2023 in New Delhi.

To flow is to expand and contract with the waves within. A tangled chaos of particles is unhindered with a deep breath and relaxation. With permission to flow, patterns emerge.

To meditate with this artwork:
- keep your eyes moving slowly, trying not to fixate on a point.
- when thoughts arise, gently let them go and return to the artwork.
- bring your awareness again, to the act of seeing moment by moment.

Flow might arise in many ways- turbulent, synchronous, circular, ephemeral, convergent, divergent, rising, waning or a mix of any of these.

[GPU-intensive, Best viewed @ 4k/full-screen. 'j' for screencap, 'v' to toggle video recording.]

metadata.name: The Yoni Project #748
metadata.description:
"The Yoni Project" is part of the live outdoor art installation - 'Computational Convergence' at India Art Fair, held from 9-12 February 2023 in New Delhi. 

'Yoni' - a Sanskrit word referring to the female reproductive organ, is often used as a symbol of the goddess and the source of life in various Indic Religions and other ancient cultures. It is one of the most sacred icons of the Hindu Shaktism tradition, with historic arts and temples dedicated to it.

'The Yoni Project' aims to pay homage to this divine feminine concept of Shakti, the embodiment of energy, power, and creativity.

NOTE: All artist royalties will be donated to Rangeen Khidki Foundation which is a youth-led feminist organization based in Kolkata. They focus on sexual and reproductive health and rights for adolescents and youth, as well as working with stakeholders such as parents, teachers, and civil organizations from marginalized backgrounds. The organization's focus is on gender justice and human rights, utilizing a pleasure affirmative lens to promote gender equality ,inclusion and diversity.

metadata.name: Tangled #84
metadata.description:
"Tangled" is a generative art project that explores the emergent behaviour of simple shapes moving according to a random flow field. While the final result is always constrained to the shape of a circle, the variation within is endless.

Instructions:
Press "p" to pause the animation.
In live mode, press 1 through 5 to save a PNG version of the final result. The following resolutions are available:
1: 400 x 400 (ideal for Twitter PFP)
2: 1000 x 1000
3: 2000 x 2000
4: 4000 x 4000
5: 5000 x 5000
Please be patient, generating the PNG may take some time!

Made with p5.js.

metadata.name: Shift #179
metadata.description:
A generative algorithm honing the power of vertical displacement.

How simple may a generative algorithm be while simultaneously staying diverse enough for each art piece to be truly unique? Shift is the result of an exploration into this space, basing its existence on two principles ‚Äî dissection and vertical shifting. Each variable in this art engine has been meticulously weighted, giving rise to high diversity and the possibility of epic combinations. 

Shift is a series of 888 unique pieces.

############

Display resolution is 1000x1400. Press ‚Äôs‚Äô (in live mode) to generate a 6000x8400 hi-res image. This may take a while to generate depending on your hardware.

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2022

metadata.name: Verdant Brut #158
metadata.description:
Verdant translates to ‚Äúlush, green‚Äù and Brut means ‚Äúdry, raw, or unrefined.‚Äù

This series is less about impressions of nature, or vegetal growth‚Ä¶ but rather the vibrant, lush world that abstract art can provide and while certain iterations may serve Brutalist aesthetics, it tries to focus on the unrefined/raw aspect of the definition with more fluid shapes that feel irregular and organic in a playful, almost adolescent way.

Palettes inspired by MOMO, Melissa Wiederrecht, Erik Swahn, Marcelo Soria-Rodr√≠guez, Paul Klee, Mareva Millarc, Ernst Mether-BorgstroÃàm, Douglas Herbert Courtenay Auburn, Jim Harris, Alayne Spafford, Man Ray, Lajos Kassak and William Lachance. While the palettes may not always reflect their trademark colors (if they even have any) they are an homage to individual pieces by the respective artists that have influenced this series in their own way.

4878 bytes of Vanilla JS with no libraries.

For more info on the chosen palettes and other inspirations, see article linked from the main project page: Regarding Verdant Brut

In live mode:
‚ÄòS‚Äô : save as png (2376‚Ää√ó‚Ää3360)
‚ÄôV‚Äô : save as svg (without grain)

URL params in live mode:
‚Äòg=n‚Äô : no grain
‚Äòg=p‚Äô : paper grain
‚Äòh=t‚Äô : high resolution mode, 5940‚Ää√ó‚Ää8400 (Chrome only)

For example, if you wanted paper grain in high resolution, append ‚Äú&g=p&h=t‚Äù to the url in live mode.

After rendering with these params, tapping 'P' will then save the png with those settings applied.

metadata.name: strokes-1 #26
metadata.description:
A generative abstract painting using layers of strokes of different size, strength and color.

The painting is rendered by simulating one stroke at a time. The recipe is similar for all paintings. First, wide faint brush strokes cover the canvas with a background texture, then a few strong brush strokes give the piece some character. After that, very fine rapid strokes give the piece some interesting detail and finally, dabs of very short brush strokes are applied for additional sense of depth. 

The rendering takes some time. With large screen sizes, you get bigger pictures (for printing!), but the rendering is slower. 

Once the work is painted, you can hit 's' to save a png file. 

There are 7 different colour schemes.
